<h3>Local Keyword Formulas</h3>
<p>Combine your services with city names for your highest-converting pages:</p>
<ul>
<li>"[service] in [city]" ,  "house cleaning in Plano"</li>
<li>"[service] near [neighborhood]" ,  "maid service near Lakewood"</li>
<li>"best [service] [city]" ,  "best deep cleaning service Dallas"</li>
<li>"[city] [service] company" ,  "Austin house cleaning company"</li>
</ul>
<p>Each city you serve should have its own landing page targeting these combinations. For a detailed process, see our <a href="/blog/keyword-research-for-blog-posts/">keyword research guide</a>.</p>
<h3>Keywords Cleaning Companies Should Skip</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>"How to clean [surface]"</strong>. DIY searches. These bring traffic but not leads. Use them sparingly for authority building, not as your primary target.</li>
<li><strong>"Cleaning supplies wholesale"</strong>. Supply chain searches. Not customers.</li>
<li><strong>"Cleaning jobs hiring near me"</strong>. Job seekers, not clients.</li>
<li><strong>"Cheap cleaning service"</strong>. Price-sensitive leads with high churn rates. Target "affordable" instead if you serve this market.</li>
</ul>
<h2>Service Pages That Convert</h2>
<p>Your website needs a dedicated page for every cleaning service you offer. A single "Services" page with bullet points will not rank for anything specific. Google rewards pages that go deep on a single service.</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" alt="Essential service pages every cleaning company website needs" src="/images/blog/cleaning-company-service-pages.webp" /></p>
<h3>Required Service Pages</h3>
<p>Create a separate, optimized page for each:</p>
<ul>
<li>House cleaning / residential cleaning</li>
<li>Deep cleaning</li>
<li>Move-in and move-out cleaning</li>
<li>Recurring cleaning (weekly, biweekly, monthly)</li>
<li>Office cleaning</li>
<li>Commercial cleaning / janitorial</li>
<li>Post-construction cleaning</li>
<li>Carpet cleaning</li>
<li>Window cleaning</li>
<li>Specialty cleaning (hoarding, Airbnb turnover, estate)</li>
</ul>
<h3>What Each Service Page Needs</h3>
<p>Every service page should include these elements:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Title tag:</strong> "[Service] in [City] | [Company Name]" under 60 characters</li>
<li><strong>H1 heading:</strong> "[Service] in [Primary City]"</li>
<li><strong>300+ words</strong> describing the service, your process, what is included, and pricing guidance</li>
<li><strong>Before-and-after photos</strong> specific to that service type</li>
<li><strong>Pricing information</strong> (even ranges like "$150-$300 for a standard deep clean" build trust)</li>
<li><strong>Customer testimonials</strong> specific to that service</li>
<li><strong>Clear CTA:</strong> "Get a Free Quote" with phone number and booking form</li>
<li><strong><a href="/blog/schema-markup-seo-guide/">Schema markup</a></strong> using LocalBusiness and Service types</li>
<li><strong>FAQ section</strong> answering the 3-4 most common questions about that service</li>
</ul>
<h3>City Landing Pages</h3>
<p>If you serve multiple cities, create a dedicated page for each. A page targeting "house cleaning in Frisco TX" ranks better than a generic "house cleaning" page for Frisco searches.</p>
<p>Each city page must include:</p>
<ul>
<li>The city name in the title, H1, and body content</li>
<li>Neighborhoods or zip codes within that city</li>
<li>References to local details (landmarks, housing types, weather factors)</li>
<li>Photos from jobs completed in that area</li>
<li>Unique content (not copy-pasted with only the city name changed)</li>
</ul>
<p>Google penalizes thin, duplicate city pages. Each page needs genuinely different content. This is where consistent <a href="/blog/seo-content-writing/">content publishing</a> at scale makes a real difference.</p>
